'''Flight mode''' (or '''airplane mode''') is a feature included in some electronic devices that deactivates [[radio transmitters]] and receivers. It mostly applies to cell phones, but it is applicable to any electronic device that transmits radio signals as its primary function. In this mode the phone's secondary features (such as its music, [[java games|games]], or scheduler) can be used safely in environments requiring minimal [[interference|radio interference]], such as [[passenger jet|planes]] and [[clinic]]s.  

The term is something of a minomer, as many [[airlines]] continue to prohibit all use of cell phones on aircraft, with some specifically announcing onboard that even cell phones with a flight-safe mode may not be used inflight.{{fact}}  As a practical matter most cell phone users simply treat flight mode as a power-saving feature or a soft-off.

The [[Motorola ROKR E1]] mobile phone was first to introduce this feature; since then other brands have followed suit.

